A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof sounds like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló by Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic shapes got the nickname "bone house".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile shards and mosaics, the scale-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
It is only on closer inspection that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the entire fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the glow of the colors even more.
The same buoyant lines and convoluted shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even gaze holes and strips.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the bustling shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was created by the renovation of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to Gaudí’s idea of an unusual and also cheaper renovation.
The Casa Batlló rental house, however, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner were created and also the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other artists and artists also worked on the design of the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí’s Casa Milá in Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given the nickname "bone house" by the local inhabitants of its organic shapes.
Others, on the other hand, called it the "thinning house" because of the special window opening mechanism.
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of Saint George, the patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system unique for the time, with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces.
Something weird already mutates her 45-degree slope.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be distracted by them.
Before the construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city fathers were so appalled by the result that they demanded remedy.
Among other things, the councillors also stumbled upon the fact that the construction with its pillars even interfered with the public sidewalk.
There was no change, however, on the contrary - only fifteen days after the district's request in this regard, Josep Batlló filed an application for the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was granted to him promptly.
The homeowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor was a company lounge, on the 3rd floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the conversion, all right angles and straight lines were eliminated and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the interconnection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and thus a larger society could conveniently chat without having to give up a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, the house received a rather unusual roof and two other floors due to Gaudí's renovation.
Also impressive is Gaudí’s play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is clothed and the lighthouses.
The play of these two colors gives the highest level of light to all floors of the house.
He simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors that absorb sunlight on the contrary.
The Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited today by anyone.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made accessible to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only in the year, on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly profitable business, the visits were maintained, yes, they were also extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not a Papenstiel, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist IDs receive a 20% discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the house dwellers and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bed rack? Women have different desires than men
Not the best bed frame, but the quality of the lying area - so mattress and rust make up the good bed.
However, these must harmoniously complement each other in order to meet the wishes of the specific user.
In the selection, many things play a role - the weight, the height, the state of health and last but not least the sex of the sleeper.
Just as important is the interior, in which mattress and rust have to subordinate themselves.
Typical example?
In a weekend home that is not regularly heated, latex mattresses are not well suited as they take much longer to "warm up".
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be turned regularly.
In fact, if they do not have enough ventilation channels in the core and are also on a solid plate, moisture accumulates: it is therefore not excluded that mold forms beneath them.
Of course, the choice also plays a role in what you are used to.
Those who have been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with a soft layer are common, will be hard to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
“All the ice hockey players who came back from the NHL have complained to me that they can no longer sleep properly here.”
"For their sagging shoulders, heels and hips, they simply need a soft layer of visco foam (Memory Foam - a shape memory polymer)."
"I also recommend this to people suffering from a disorder of the nervous system, among other things, so that they can receive the 'information' from the joints and the skin poorly," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That's why I bought many ice hockey players years ago, but also other customers these mattresses with visco foam (memory foam).
"Today, this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses offer, among others, the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico."
And you don’t have to be a famous ice hockey player to appreciate the benefits of visco foam.
This “miracle” actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the absorbed heat, in other words, it clinges directly to the warm body.
Nowhere does it squeeze, at night you don’t roll around like after a hard fight.
You just sleep a lot better.
The viscoelastic foam also offers protection against decubitus (wound fire).
When choosing the mattress size, you should still add to the height the length of the soles of the feet, that is, about 21 to 34 cm.
Both men and women, who are 180 cm tall, need a bed of 210 to 220 cm long.
Each of the sleepers should be at least 90 cm wide, together 180 cm.
For single beds, for example single beds, 120 to 140 cm are attached.
For convenience and also for any visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal bed width: "If you are lying on your back, there should still be enough space for the slightly angled arms", advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, the master of upholstery and room furnishers, who has been devoting herself for years to the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own rust and their own mattress, but be careful when shopping so that the mattresses are equally high.
Otherwise, there is no choice but to mount the grate at different heights and this is far from possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with a spring skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters should fall on the mold layer and the fine padding.
"You can't feel the feathers with your hand or when you sit down," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a special type of rust.
Fully upholstered beds with mattress and base like mattressed twins have nothing to look for in the bedroom.
These mattresses cannot be ventilated and the cover cannot be washed, which is already common today.
And since one loses between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat in a single night, it is clear that after five to seven years the mattress will slowly turn into a huge (and clogged) screen.
This is also why professionals reject advertising slogans that promise a lifetime of up to 25 years for mattresses, even a lifetime warranty.
Every thing has its if and but.
And therefore a practical advice from the dealers: With mattresses of 120 or 140 cm width, do not shy away from the hygiene of the washable, detachable covers, yet it is recommended to use a mattress protector, which can be easily removed and washed.
Although today mattress covers are usually made with a round zipper, so that after opening you get two halves (important for the washing process and the size of the washing machine!), the manipulation with larger mattresses, especially executed alone, often implies the unequal fight between David and Goliath.
Do they have a solid plate in bed instead of a rust?
Get out of here!
Or at most for a bed for unloved guests and for a single night.
Also, they should rather provide the plate with ventilation holes (if none are already in it) and use mattresses with spring skeleton and 15 cm minimum height with so-called pocket spring core and fine padding.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong on such a substrate.
Latex or sandwich mattresses (including combinations of latex and coconut) are suitable for non-adjustable lattice slats with 14 to 18 spring slats (lamellae), with a greater number of lattice slats, i.e. 28 and more spring slats, with lordosis support in the lumbar area and the possibility of regulating the lattice hardness.
Adjustable slatted grids do not include mattresses with a spring skeleton, as they do not react to the ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the spring strips, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This involves a special fastening of the spring strips, which makes it possible to press the spring strips or even to angle them in such a way that they allow the shoulder of the sleeper to sink at a point.
Especially for men with broad shoulders an important thing.
There are even mattress manufacturers who have started using soft zones for the shoulder area on "master mattresses".
The ladies are also thought of - they are given these soft zones in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, point-elastic wing spring systems (lattoflex) or grates with point-elastic contact pads with so-called multitorsion suspension are designed.
The pressure is distributed over several points, which reduces the voltage.
But - if you use a bad (too big and full) pillow for the right mattress and the right rust, most of the benefits will be lost.
Here again a rule of thumb: the pillow should support the head, its tips should only reach to the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
Ideally, a 50 x 60 cm pillow appears, as the Scandinavians like, for example.
In the side position, the cushion should balance the height of the shoulder (together with the shoulder relief zone in the grate or the soft zone in the mattress).
