"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health burdens, Ms. Eeles added.
In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain tracked more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men at the same time.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
These men had the same likelihood of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
However, in men whose index fingers were longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to sixty percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which form as early as prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone is the one that accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
