The discovery of a foreign species of bacteria that can live on arsenic opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible without the elements previously considered necessary for life.
"This organism has two options."
"He needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
“That makes it very special, even though it’s almost some kind of ‘foreign’ life form,” said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears in the online issue of Science magazine on Thursday.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, as the scientists found out, the bacterium in California’s Mono Lake continues to grow even if it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
“You wonder what else is possible,” said co-author Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists must recognize life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details of the discovery were announced gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery “shows that in other planetary systems organisms can initiate biochemical processes with the help of other elements, and that the ‘standard elements’, which we believe are absolutely essential, are not necessarily fixed,” said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
“This work is novel, because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures, one element can be replaced by another,” Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose the Mono Lake because of the high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she assumed that microbes exposed to both may be able to replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of the arsenic is mainly due to its chemically similar behavior to phosphorus."
“This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another.”
"But the difference is so great that arsenic acts differently than phosphorus, it enters our biochemical system where it smears almost everything," Anbar explains.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing arsenic concentration, which adapted and grew.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, it can survive in arsenic, but it shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon, where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but so far there has not been a working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, so science has assumed that early life forms used it.
“This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than it did in the early Earth age,” said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
