"Stand straight!"
"Look straight ahead!"
"Show them," he whispered, "how pretty girls are!"
Four girls, barely grown out of teenage years, wearing white gloves and identical olive-green jackets and trousers, were stubborn.
Four pairs of black pumps were in straight line.
Four neat hats sat perfectly on the hair held with blue and white stripes.
"To me, they look average," Mr. Tang remarks in contempt.
"Models are pretty."
Several governments have already tried to polish the image of China’s city inspectors.
In a city, all new applicants must have a university degree.
The Guangdong province introduced a bright blue uniform instead of the grey-green one.
Wuhan in Central China replaced violence with low rigidity: in 2009, 50 officials reportedly circled an incorrectly placed snack cart and stared at the operator until it packed up and left the place after half an hour.
Xindu, a city district in Chengdu with 680,000 inhabitants, wants to fundamentally change the image.
Since 2003, 13 women have been reinforcing urban police strips, specially selected for their appearance, good figure and youth.
They are meant to give the coarsely slaughtered police a softer, feminine aspect.
But unfortunately, Scarlett Johansson would hardly be able to improve the bad image that the Chinese have of these city commandos.
Right, so the critics.
Unlike the police, these officials may enforce the city laws only by means of fines or other administrative penalties.
However, the Chinese media routinely show a different picture.
In January 2008, officials in Hubei province beat a spectator to death as he filmed them with his mobile phone, shooting a protest against a dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing officials was stolen and published on the Internet, describing how criminals can be beaten without bloodshed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon dealer suffered brain injuries after a handshake with five officials.
A violent video game that can be downloaded from the Internet shows trained officials in China in an attack on street traders.
"Chengguan scares the government," the national newspaper China Daily lamented last year, after further controversy over the tactics.
The newspaper called for “really thorough cleansing.”
Skeptics consider the current approach to be clearly insufficient.
When the district was looking for eight female recruits by advertisement in October, an editorial in the Beijing Evening News asked whether the women had real tasks or should only serve as an optical distraction.
Probably both.
According to the job advertisement, women between the ages of 18 and 22 were searched for with good figure and "harmonic facial features".
They should be above average size - over 1.5m or 5 feet, 2 1/2 inches.
The employment relationship ends at the age of 26.
According to the officials, the activity for women over 25 is too physically exhausting.
"The most important thing is their image," an unnamed district official told quasi-government website Rednet.com.
"Whether the candidates get the job depends first of all on their outward appearance, such as height, weight, facial traits, etc."
Then comes temperament and "inner qualities".
"Female Chengguan are like flower vases," he said, adding, "but beyond that, they still have other duties."
Zheng Lihua, deputy head of the district’s city administration, would not agree with this description,
However, he admitted that in China, size requirements in job advertisements are not unusual for both genders.
The same applies to uniform facial features.
Whether this is to be equated with good looks is controversial in China.
But people with disabilities or physical disability do not need to apply.
"Unfortunately, we cannot use lame or buckling here," said Mr. Zheng.
"Your image wouldn't be good."
Liu Yi, who patrols on Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22, has apple pies and a well-shaped mouth.
She did not feel sexist that so much emphasis was placed on her appearance.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" she asks with an ironic look.
Her colleague with the digging, 21-year-old Xu Yang, commented, “We have the task of representing the image of the city.”
According to their accounts, they do not regret the short-term attitude, as they have more ambitious career plans than simply shunning traders through the streets to prevent them from doing business.
Every morning there are about twelve street traders who try to sell as many rolls and tofu dishes as possible on foot or by bike before they are driven away.
"Mr. Wang, please get out of here."
"We have told you this so many times!" explains Mr. Xu to a trader who had fled on foot and had temporarily abandoned his pasta kitchen attached to a bicycle cart.
According to the officials, the activity is monotonous rather than exhausting.
“It’s almost the same every day,” explains Huang Jing, 20, who studies in leisure sales.
"All routine."
One reason for this is that female officials are not allowed to confiscate traders’ goods, like their male counterparts.
They can only threaten criminals to report them to their male superiors.
This is intended to protect them from public hostility to which officials in China are often exposed.
This year, hundreds of residents of Kunming, the capital of Yunnan province, ravaged after rumors circulated that Chengguan officials had killed a merchant.
More than a dozen police officers and Chenguan officials were injured in the nightly incident, 14 government vehicles were thrown down or set on fire.
Xindu has been spared such violence so far.
However, unrest cannot be ruled out.
Just two blocks away from the quiet Baonguang Square, where the female officers patrolled that morning, over 50 people gathered at a street corner.
Officials confiscated a motorcycle that was repaired on the sidewalk instead of in a workshop.
The owner screamed Zeter and Murder.
After 15 minutes of hesitation, the grim-faced officers made their way to their vehicles and drove off on the motorcycle and its owner.
Li Xuedong, 40, a male police coordinator, was left behind, turning his white nameplate around to remain anonymous.
Like their colleagues, the coordinators - men over 40 - play a purely supportive role.
But they were not trained in presenting a clean image.
"Sometimes we go verbally."
"Sometimes, but also physically," Mr. Li explains soberly.
“Most of the time, people start fighting.”
Prosecutor will not charge Senator Ensign
Attorneys at the Justice Department have acquitted Senator John Ensign of charges raised against him following his affair with a former election helper and his attempt to provide her husband with lobbying, the Senator's lawyers announced Wednesday.
This decision ends the heaviest charge against Senator Ensign, the Republican from Nevada, until the scandal that drove headlines nationwide and put a damper on his career, he was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012.
As Senator Ensign’s office announced, he was “highly pleased” with the ruling after the one-year investigation.
However, the Senate Ethics Committee could still impose a disciplinary penalty.
According to Ensign’s lawyers, they were informed by the Ministry of Justice that the investigations against Senator Ensign have been discontinued and that there are no further charges in this matter.
The Justice Department did not comment on the case.
The ruling came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, and they believe there was sufficient evidence that Ensign violated the lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails, and other documents first released in the New York Times in October 2009 gave rise to the suspicion that Ensign Douglas Hampton, one of his electoral assistants, helped to make lucrative orders to buy his silence over an affair with Hampton's wife Cynthia.
Cynthia Hampton served as Treasurer during an election campaign for Ensigns.
Ensign contacted some political friends to get Hampton to work, and according to the documents and interrogations, he took over for them after hiring Hampton's lobbying.
Since Hampton was recently on Ensign’s electoral team, he was not allowed to lobby for his former employer or the entire Senate for a year.
According to ethics experts, the unusual agreement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the case, violated the so-called ban on turn-door lobbying.
According to the published indications, “it appears to be an agreement and a violation of the revolving door statutes,” according to Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients targeted by the government.
While the Justice Department officially declined to disclose the reasons for the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethic lawyers said the ministry appears very cautious in picking up political charges after a variety of defeats have been pursued by the media with great interest, including last year’s decision to drop the charges against former Senator Ted Steven’s misconduct.
Prosecutors “are obviously terrifying,” said Melanie Sloan, chairwoman of the Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington Association, a group of lawyers who have brought various charges against Mr. Ensign.
“This basically means that senior government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them,” she added.
Paul Coggins, chief defender of Mr. Ensign, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a prosecutor on Monday and another the next day informing him that the ministry would not bring any lawsuits against his client.
Mr. Ensign’s defenders had cooperated with prosecutors to convince them that the Senator, as his office repeated in a statement on Wednesday, “acted in accordance with the law.”
Mr. Coggins refused to explain in more detail the legal arguments he had made to the prosecutors.
“I’m not going to go into the details of the conversation between the Ministry of Justice and me, but let’s just say that we believe we made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the federal election commission decided to stop the investigation into a separate lawsuit by the ethics group, according to which a payment of $96,000 from Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated the federal election law.
The election commission said there was not enough evidence that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a large Nevada company that supported the senator for a long time, was one of the companies where Mr. Hampton found lobbying work thanks to the help of Mr. Ensign.
An e-mail from December 2008 proves that, after the company continued Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensing’s Chief of Staff, John Lopez, had a conversation with Mr. Hampton, telling him that he was “belling” at the Home Office on a matter.
Mr. Ensign also had an appointment for lunch with Mr. Hampton and another client from Nevada, Allegiant Air, and asked the Minister of Transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after it had discontinued Mr. Hampton for lobbying.
When information about this affair first came out last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his voters and resigned his position in the Senate, where he had ranked fourth in the Republican rankings.
After noticing for many months, Mr. Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he was seeking a third term in the Senate.
Announcing that Mr. Ensign is no longer the target of police investigations, his press spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hopes the Ethics Committee will follow the example of the Justice Department very quickly and cease its investigations.
“Senator Ensign is looking forward to continuing his hard work serving the people of Nevada,” she said.
Cheshire call draws attention on Twitter
Half a dozen of them tapped into the riots in the courtroom.
Within minutes, they sent their reports of gruesome witness testimony via Twitter.
In the end, the defense said, there were more than 140,000 Twitter messages about the rape process and children chained at beds in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the carefully pursued trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was accused of killing three members of a Cheshire, Connecticut family, will come to an official end when the judgement on the death sentence issued by the jury falls.
However, Mr. Hayes’ lawyers have already filed applications in court, outlining the reasons for an appeal, and which the courts will deal with for years to come.
One of the most provocative reasons is that the intense reporting on the process – including the extensive use of Twitter by average reporters – led to a “circus atmosphere” and such a widespread, immediate penetration of upheaval details that the jury had been impermissibly influenced by public outrage.
This objection could prompt the appeals courts to examine whether new technologies make new rules necessary in the courtroom.
“Just as I have experienced it during this trial, I think it’s really a danger if the entry of new technologies into the courtroom affects everyone’s right to a fair trial,” said Thomas J. Ullman, Mr. Haye’s chief defender.
The presiding judge of the Supreme Court, Jon C. Blue, dismissed the motions briefly and fluently last week when he said that the New Media would be “carefully controlled” and that there was no evidence that the jury had been driven by passions.
But that was certainly not the last word on this matter.
For decades, court claims have found that reporting on famously infamous cases raises doubts about the fairness of a trial.
In its historic 1966 ruling, the Supreme Court of the United States overturned the ruling against Dr. Sam Sheppard, an osteopath from Cleveland who allegedly killed his wife, saying in his ruling that there was a “carnival atmosphere in the courtroom” because of the New Media.
Some believe that the TV series and feature film "On the Escape" is based on this crime.
Some lawyers say court claims that Mr. Haye’s conviction a half-century later might follow the argument that new rules have become necessary to regulate the communication paths from the courtroom that were still unimaginable at the time of the Dr. Sheppard case.
“There is a good reason to be concerned about the influence of the New Media in lawsuits that are being pursued by a broad public,” said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School who investigated the death penalty in Connecticut.
Professor Donohue said some appeals courts might be fascinated by the idea that restricting immediate communication out of the courtroom could make trials fairer.
The Twitter affair is just one of many that Mr. Hayes’ lawyers present to discuss for years and thus delay a conviction.
For example, the defenders also claim that Mr. Hayes may have already been pre-convicted when Judge Blue had not allowed them to test the reactions of potential jurors by showing them gruesome crime scene photos during the juror selection.
Some of the jurors said photos of the victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and their breeders, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11, had filled them with aversion.
The defenders say they would also question the constitutionality of the death penalty constitution, arguing that the judge mistakenly exchanged a juror who had been a critic of the prosecutor’s office, and that he put inadmissible pressure on the judgment when he made the unusual decision to release the jury over the weekend.
The jurors were not isolated.
But their arguments about the influence of detailed reporting on the process may attract the greatest interest.
In a ruling they filed last month, they found that the case had dominated the news in Connecticut and was discussed by the candidates during the election campaign for the governor’s office and for the American Senate.
They argued that the New Media continually reignited the flames of emotions about the case.
“Such a daily rush of media pipsters, cameras and reporters outside the courtroom,” the lawyers wrote, “has not been experienced before in New Haven and perhaps even nationwide.”
Their focus on Twitter reporting is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists said that the claim that these direct news items are more exhilarating than reports that are being returned more slowly is an anti-technology look that impoverishes reporting on future processes.
But some lawyers said appeals courts would often face the argument that social and technical changes needed adaptation by the courts.
Mr. Hayer's lawyers reinforce this claim.
In their objection, they referred to the 1966 Supreme Court ruling, in which Dr. Sheppard’s conviction for reporting was lifted, and made it clear that the New Media required new rules.
“This case,” they wrote, “represents Sheppard against Maxwell of the 21st century.”
Can courtesy connect the separation?
After a campaign of insults and negativity, little politeness broke out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of real two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before one quickly returns to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and congressional leaders gave no breakthrough on the major issues that had to be dealt with during the so-called “lame duck session,” the session at the end of a period of government in which no more decisions will be made.
According to all you hear, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor an observance of their shared responsibility, but rather an empty episode of a partisan accumulation of points.
The public meeting of the President’s deficit commission on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that continue to exist between members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates mutual respect that covers up the ideological divide that continues to separate members from each other.
This is hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - in which one of the other signs of willingness to cooperate and compromise, while trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after a renewed party warfare.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, donations, health or accruals, the two sides are miles from each other.
At least for a short time, Washington voted mildly in the November election.
“No question, the tone has changed,” said Pete Wehner, an official Bush administration official now working for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“This is inevitable after the elections.
Elections awaken party passions that are dying again.
And that's good."
In some issues, especially those on the agenda of the “lame duck session,” Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution.”
Bush’s tax cuts ended at the end of the year, and no one supports that.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or even all of them, whether temporarily or permanently.
Similarly, a compromise on increased unemployment pay is to be expected, albeit only because Republicans cannot afford to believe favored tax cuts for the rich while denying support to unemployed workers.
After the meeting in the White House on Tuesday, optimism has risen that one can agree on these issues during the "lame duck session" and at the same time ratify the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful collaboration on urgent issues of the lame duck session does not necessarily have to lead to lasting cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
“After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,” he said.
Wehner is also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - which leads to true cooperation.
“I see a lot of what happens from now until 2012 as a pre-match, or shadow boxes, for the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the presentation of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who served their formation.
However worried the Republican leaders may be that they are playing too high poker, they know that they must try to keep their promises to cut government spending and override health reform.
These party lines are already clear in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include a tax reform and the raising of some taxes, as well as the raising of the pension age and the lowering of government spending.
Vice-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and have, in their own opinion, pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the commission to make their plan an official recommendation and they are struggling very hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the panel, because in financial matters, at least today, there is little room or little sympathy for compromises.
Galston predicts two phases in the fight between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take place next year in the form of party clashes when Republicans challenge Obama over the state budget, taxes and health care system, later followed by a phase of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the bias of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties must pay careful attention to the public response.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a larger ideological divide between Obama and the Congressional Republicans than it was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a pure prelude to a much more far-reaching election in 2012.
From this point of view, the courtesy that is being shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take a lot more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the questions that still separate the two.
Leaked US document portrays Moscow as a port of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of the "Kleptocracy" and it passes a portion of the bribes and protection money it collects to the Kremlin, according to the US Embassy in Russia in a memo in February.
Both the police and the state security service are blackmailing large amounts of protection so that they can maintain their expensive living standards in Moscow, it is said.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal gangs.
Every layer of bureaucracy -- what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called a "vertical of authority" -- takes its share of the money that the ladders move upwards.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted on his homepage by WikiLeaks on Tuesday.
The memo is based on sources whose names have been edited.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still Moscow’s mayor, and it accuses him of corruption.
He was fired in October by President Dmitry Medvedev, but there is hardly any evidence that he would have been cleared up in the meantime.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a well-known construction company, have repeatedly rejected allegations of corruption for years, and he has won numerous libel lawsuits against such allegations.
In September, he told a Russian television station when he was asked for a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: “It’s crazy, it’s dirty, it’s dirty.”
> An incredibly large number of Russians believe that their society is corrupt, according to surveys.
But it is unusual, as the ambassador’s report does, for individuals to be named, and it is unheard of that this is done by a diplomat of a foreign country.
“The direct link between the Moscow government and crime has led some to call it ‘interfered’ and conclude that the government acts more like a kleptocrat than a government,” the memo said.
“Criminal elements enjoy a ‘kryshna’ (a term from the world of criminals/mafia, which literally means ‘roof’ or protection), which extends over the police, state security (FSB), the service supervisory authority (MVD) and the office of the prosecutor as well as the entire Moscow government bureaucracy.
Experts have discovered a three-layer structure within the criminal world of Moscow.
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"FSB, MVD and the militia are on the second stage."
“Lastly, ordinary criminals and criminal inspectors are on the lowest level.”
“This is an incompetent system in which criminal groups close a gap in some areas because the city offers no help whatsoever.”
The report continues to say that the FSB is collecting money from the largest companies and that the police are arresting small businessmen.
One source, it is said, “explained that Moscow’s business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and FSB (and not from organized crime) as they not only have more weapons, resources, and power than the criminals, but also because they are protected by the law.”
"For this reason, protection by criminal gangs is no longer as in demand as it used to be."
The memo notes that while collecting funds is comprehensive, the protection itself will not be very modest; even those who pay are sometimes arrested.
Those who do not pay find their business closed very quickly - due to one or other pretext.
Medvedev has spoken several times about fighting corruption, but at the same time noted that he has made little progress.
The memo of the message contains descriptions of men who go to the Kremlin with suitcases presumably full of money.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev must rely on the bureaucrats," Georgy Satarov, director of Indem, a Moscow expert commission, said recently in an interview.
“But he’s part of this bureaucracy.”
“It is not part of the political class because a political class no longer exists in Russia.”
Without politicians, without an opposition, without a separation of powers, he says, corruption is inevitable.
Nationwide, it estimates, corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
The country ranks 154th in a recent survey of the global perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries ranked from "less corrupt" to "most corrupt").
The revelation of the memo of the American embassy, which happened late in the evening after Moscow, will certainly cause displeasure within the Russian government, although since Luzhkov can be accused of Moscow’s mistakes, it can also be a way for the Kremlin to claim that the problems are solved.
In an interview with Larry King for CNN, Putin claimed that the WikiLeaks documents could be a fake and reacted angry to the revelation that American diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
“The truth is that it’s about our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policy in this country,” he said.
“But to be honest, we wouldn’t have expected this to happen with such arrogance, with such pressure and in such an unethical way, you know.”
Khmer Rouge Veterans Forced to Confront Past
In a dimly lit, concrete classroom with dirty and peeling walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School reminds the man who built it, the later Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
“He was a good leader and he took care of his people,” said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Due to his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule known as "the butcher", the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge castle in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals and bridges, developed the infrastructure and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
Yet this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-standing supporters are being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed the victims to publicly confront the people who once supported the regime.
In June, the government distributed a schoolbook that for the first time tells children of former soldiers the history of the Khmer Rouge.
And in July, a community court of the UN and Cambodia first sentenced a former member of the Khmer Rouge, when it sentenced the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture chamber, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these developments, fear grew among the Khmer Rouge veterans of Alnlong Vengs, making their efforts to reconcile and reintegrate into Cambodia's society more difficult.
“There is still rejection and fear in the former Khmer Rouge, but they have no power to do anything,” said Chhang Youk, head of Cambodia’s Documentation Center, an independent organization investigating the regime.
For her, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil.
“It splits families.”
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of disease, overhaul or starvation.
When the Vietnamese invaded and in 1979 the Pol Pot-Ied government overthrew, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to Cambodia’s border to Thailand.
Here they spread unrest until December 1998, when the last movement surrendered.
When Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their base in the western mountains and jungles of Cambodia, Ta Mok drew the next generation to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, when a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to run over to government, leading to the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuan Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died a natural death in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had not given in, was arrested in 1999 by government forces in the Dangrek Mountains.
He died in 2006 in Phnom Penh Prison, where he waited for his trial.
When their patrons no longer protected them, most former Khmer Rouge fighters fled into the depleting poverty of rural Cambodia and many kept the movement in nostalgic memory.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local government posts because they laid down their weapons, the ordinary soldiers remained poor, uneducated peasants.
“These people have benefited very little from the surrender,” said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are anchored in the utopian agricultural ideology of the regime."
"They grew up without any professional knowledge."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Rhmer Rouge in 1974 as a teenager, fought in the jungle for Anlang Veng before settling down in 1998 to lead a life as a poor rice farmer.
“Life under the Khmer Rouge was good,” he said.
"Ta Mok gave everyone something to eat."
“But now life is hard because we have to take care of ourselves.”
The ongoing Khmer Rouge tribunal has also raised concerns here.
Earlier next year, the court will try to bring Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, as well as Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister, to justice.
The mandate of the court is to condemn the ancient leaders and those who are primarily responsible for the atrocities, but it is not said whether it will pursue further acts beyond these four cases.
This has helped little to alleviate the fears in Anlong Veng.
Current media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who had been district chief in Manteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told officials at the Documentation Centre of Cambodia that she had led the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project in which thousands of forced laborers were believed to have died.
On a hot evening Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to her wooden house on a dirty road outside Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows on the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss their past with the Khmer Rouge.
If the court brought her, she would refuse to go, she said.
“Cambodia lives in peace and stability,” she said.
"If there were no more persecution, there would be war here."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who fled the Khmer Rouge in 1878, has also repeatedly warned that the situation would become uncertain if the court charged more suspects, although experts and historians are discussing this.
"Cambodia has to dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But the confrontation with the past is what Cambodia needs to do to be able to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation center.
“Reconciliation with the Khmer eras means bringing the broken pieces together,” he said.
“It is our duty to put these broken parts together so that we can understand everything.”
The center created the first government-approved schoolbook on the Khmer Rouge, the 75-page "History of Democratic Cambodia".
It distributed the book in June in Anlong Veng as an appendix to the High School History Book of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages about the Khmer Rouge.
As often in Cambodia, the young people in Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city’s links to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new schoolbook helps students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted skeptically when he brought the book home to read it.
“My family rejects many parts of the book and the court,” he said.
“They’re suspicious because they’re not sure how many people are being convicted by the court.”
Such resistance makes the reconciliation process complex and complicated, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the schoolbook and the court gradually gain influence,” he said.
The Khmer Rouge still has a powerful attraction here.
Above in the Dangrek mountains, a path overgrown by shrubs and dirty with plastic garbage leads to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a rusty sheet metal roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here after his death in 1998 on a pile of tires.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a cell phone saleswoman on the street, said she doesn’t know much about the man who was burned here.
“But he has a strong spirit and a lot of people here are going to pray to him,” she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday and later on the day she wanted to go to Pol Pot's last resting place, where she will lay a bush of ripe bananas - in the hope that it will bring her happiness.
