On the contrary, this is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
Germany is taking a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which conflicts with the maintenance of the ancient traditions of a large part of its partners.
Given the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: the reintroduction of the German Mark - although this currently sounds more like science fiction - , supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a reshaping of the euro according to German proposals. This means: more macroeconomic control; strict financial management; punishment of countries that exceed the requirements; more possible the cessation of payments of some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adaptation measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been distinguished for some time, so there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled a constitutional reform out of the sleeve to prevent this from 2016.
This was the first sign of the divergence between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was set by the Central European country when Merkel painfully pushed the decision to save Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the public opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel came out again with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union agreements to allow the rescue of a country while at the same time requiring private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it drove the Irish crisis and all of the following.
However, their proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will be participating in the reform of the European Union, which will allow these measures to take place from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that, even if unpopular measures have to be taken now, the old way of working the euro will no longer exist from this date onwards.
2013 will be the year of birth of a new currency area in which the offending countries will be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent, and in this case the private sector will have to bear part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we need to pursue a hard course of growth, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness, as well as positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as mentioned by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly to not understand it.
It is not just about reducing the government deficit to 3% by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to cheat on ourselves.
I hope that the current turmoil will move into more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities that are offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) points out that despite criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in her own house has prepared its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn’t look like anything would change.
Among the options considered is the fact that we would have to leave the euro area full of poorly reputable countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us it warned us.
Sport and bypassing rules
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against Ajax show the spirit of invention, but not the willingness to circumvent a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League resulted in a lot of ink being shed on whether it was an unsportsman or not and whether both players should possibly be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) time and played several fouls so that the referee would show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next league game against Auxerre and thus enter the next phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club’s coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules followed in this sport.
Part of the debate about the case is that a team from the football club Real Madrid (who professed nobility and honor in his anthem and on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the lead, and the dramatization by Mourinho, who has added an episode more to his long history than a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is about whether this behaviour, which is explicitly prohibited by the statutes, does not contradict the principles of sport, that is to say whether these acts constitute an circumvention of the rules, in fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not compromised by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is avoiding the opposing players from gaining an unjustified benefit from the opposing team.
The paradox of the action of Real Madrid players is that it does not correspond to what we normally mean by wrong play or bypassing rules, because the bypass of the rule was not carried out in secret to avoid a sanction, but it should be as noticeable as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage did the offenders draw from the deliberate fouls.
It should be emphasized here that the rival was not put in a less favourable position nor were any advantages required for the game being played, because the obvious result of this action was that their own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players begin the next phase of the Champions League game without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term, to a certain degree, uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually retire, and players will receive a penalty with this approach and move into the second card cycle, in which they retire less than in the first card cycle due to card accumulation.
It is not so clear whether it really is an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the sports spirit, which includes strategic decisions to make the most of the regulations.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent a sanction (that would actually be a clear case of circumvention), they wanted to choose when to undergo it.
They made a strategic decision without evading a penalty or fleeing from it.
Although the boundary between inventiveness and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the controversy arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the rule transmission provoked.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
