President Barack Obama today supported nationwide mobilization in support of the Dream Act - the law to legalize undocumented students with a message on his personal blog on the social network Twitter.
“If you’re in favor of passing the Dream Act, call your senators and push for the passing of that law,” Obama tweeted.
His briefing contains a cyberlink to a broader document that calls on the public to come in touch with their senators, as the vote of the law is imminent.
“With your voice we’re waiting for, the time has come to listen to you,” he said.
The news was spread after the 42 Republican senators threatened to block all votes for any law except expanding tax cuts from Bush’s time and funding the government would be expanded.
Such a blockade, announced on a letter signed by the 42 Republican senators, could impact the vote on the Dream Act and other projects such as the ratification of the new START agreement with Russia against the spread of nuclear weapons.
Asked about the Republican blockade of the Dream Act and other projects, presidential spokesman Robert Gibbs said he trusted that once the tax issue was resolved, a timetable could be set for the remaining projects.
"I think we still have a lot of time..."
"We all agree that the tax issue must be resolved before the end of the year..."
“I think we can make an agreement on it at any time and then we can plan the rest,” he said.
The chairman of the Democratic majority in the Senate, Harry Reid, announced on Tuesday that "he would ask for a vote at the end of the debate" to allow the Dream Act law, which would allow the initiative to legalize undocumented students to be voted in the Senate from next Thursday, although next week would be more likely.
The version of the Dream Act Act or the Law of the American Dream would legalize about 800,000 young people who immigrated to the United States when they were not yet sixteen years old, have lived in that country for the past five years and are enrolled in a higher education institution or in the army.
But the advocates of the law need sixty votes to pass the initiative, which is why they depend on the votes of a handful of Republicans. At the moment, the organizations of the advocates of this project are organizing an intense influence on the passage of the law.
The Democrats, the majority of whom support the Dream Act, have 58 seats.
However, one of them, Senator Ben Nelson of Nebraska, said he would vote against it and only one Republican, Richard Lugar of Indiana, has announced his support for the law.
That is why the defenders of the Dream Act must get several Republicans on their side in case other Democrats decide to turn their backs on the initiative.
Among the most successful Republicans are those from Maine, Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins, as well as Senator George Lemieux from Florida, who took office as Senator Mel Martínez.
Other Republicans who supported the Dream Act in the past are Orrin Hatch from Utah and Kay Bailey Hutchinson from Texas, but they said they would no longer support it on another occasion.
Another Republican who had advocated for the law, John McCain, has not yet established his stance.
Although the House of Representatives has a different version, analysts agree that the Dream Act in the Senate faces the biggest obstacles.
Putting your finger in the wound with literature
