"I understand that with sex in language, but... The finger in the wound? What is expected of me?" asked the writer Luisa Valenzuela, who was supposed to open the second round of 'Los plagues de la langue', a cycle that celebrated Spanish-speaking literature and used the subtitle of her question on this occasion.
The finger in the wound... "brings us into trouble", the Argentine writer spitted sweetly to the audience, which consisted mainly of young people who gathered at the International Book Fair in Guadalajara (FIL) to attend this round table moderated by Marisol Shultz, at which Valenzuela, Sergio Ramírez, Mayra Montero and Luis García participated.
Luisa Valenzuela read a text, which she dedicated to Gonzalo Celorio, and then characterized Shultz as a great story. Luisa tells in the first person and is the protagonist who is looking to learn what a "wound" is, and goes from doctor to doctor, from which she receives no answer, but hints for the guide of her story
She leaves the infectologist convinced: "Patience is not my strength, maybe it is my wound."
Finally, after a frustrating approach to the traumatologist, who took her breath in the middle of the corridor, and who explains to her that wound is not a scientific term, the psychoanalyst reveals the secret: "the wound is the truly open, the symbolic is the scar."
The main character of the narrative sighs relieved and concludes that she "only learned from the wound that it was really open and did not exist", but she is convinced that the desire for language and its traps are mixed.
Valenzuela, the writer, played with both.
The Nicaraguan Sergio Ramírez also presented a delightful narrative he called 'Praise of Invention', in which the finger in the wound is not mentioned, but is discovered.
With allusions to magical realism, he tells of a famous sorceress who touched the clouds, brought back men who traveled far or restored the virtue lost by a girl. The narrative made a twist and told of America, the great novel that was not lacking from the beginning to his own chronicler, and he quoted the story of Bernal Díaz del Castillo.
“Cervantes, who invited us all, mocked the fake witness who appeared in the stories portrayed as true, but in other ways the history of America would never have been told — with imagination that even the feeling of shame disappeared.”
However, he emphasizes that "it is the madmen and liars who best imagine things", and there reality and lie approach each other, where one no longer knows which side belongs to the narrative, where the fictional literature reaches the summit.
This is actually called the Cervantes tradition.
"From him we inherited to be what is told."
When it was Mayra Montero’s turn, the writer commented and praised the variety of interpretations to which the FIL’s invitation to the round table ‘The Finger in the Wound’ had contributed.
The Cuban and Puerto Rican devoted her contribution to the great wound of the social violence that plagues her country - like all of Latin America - as a result of the struggles over the drug trade.
“I believe that good literature, good poetry, good songs contain a tacit, unintentionally planned commitment,” she explained, after stressing that literature is communication and commitment that builds up between the author and the readers as in a “chemical reaction.”
The evening was decided by the Spanish poet Luis García Montero, whose contribution also raised "this finger of the committed writer in the wound of the writer".
He noted that in a fast-paced world, intellectual habits and control of consciousness will also result in dogmatism, forgetting that "behind every confirmation is a small no and behind every denial a small yes."
To be in possession of our thought and reality, we must nuance: and nuance often means to put a finger in the wound and to harass those who feel much more comfortable when they think in the form of caricatures, in black and white, in prefabricated ideas without nuances, and also to harass the powerful who prefer to write the world in black and white.
