The U.S. changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must present themselves to the Consulate before their meeting with the service offices to apply for a visa; costs will be shortened in this way.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa at the U.S. embassy and consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves at the Consulate at the Service Offices for Applying for Visas (ASC, the initial letters in English) before they meet.
ASC staff shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be reviewed by the Consulate prior to the interview.
The new method has certain benefits for aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa decreases, because it is no longer necessary to pay separately the appointment agreement, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed over.
The applicant only makes a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the counterparty to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa application (including visa for temporary workers) and $390 for dealers and investors.
Those who only want to renew their visa do not have to have a conversation in the consulate, they only have to introduce themselves to the nearest ASC, where they present their documents and their fingerprints are taken.
Since the biometric data is collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the conversation in the consulate remain there less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa at the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the service surcharge of $26.
Further information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visum-FAQs.html
NASA announces the discovery of extraterrestrial life
The North American Space Agency called for a press conference to present a finding tomorrow that will have an impact on the search for living things in space.
The U.S. National Aerospace Agency (NASA) is announcing an astrobiological discovery tomorrow, Thursday, that could confirm the theory of the existence of extraterrestrial life.
The discovery will be presented tomorrow at 1 p.m. at a press conference at NASA’s headquarters in Washington by experts in astrobiology, a science that investigates the origin, development, distribution and future of life in the universe.
In convening the press conference, NASA assured that it would present “a prudential find for the search for extraterrestrial life,” sparking speculation among experts from other countries.
The discovery could prove the theory that human-like creatures could exist in hostile environments previously thought to be uninhabitable, hypothesizing that they could transform into intelligent creatures - just like humans - if their living conditions improved.
Apparently, it is a microbe found at the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment believed to be too toxic to all imaginable life forms because the lake is heavily arsenic-containing.
In some way, the microbe uses arsenic as a survival resource. Considering this ability, the chances are that there could be similar life on other planets that do not have our protective atmosphere.
When these organisms metabolize the arsenic, according to the astrobiologists, it is proven that "there is actually a different form of life, a second form of life that differs from that known to us."
The Space Agency will announce the actual reach of its fund at the press conference on Thursday.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars, and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists studying Titan (the largest moon on Saturn) on the question of whether its chemical composition resembles that of Earth.
