Global plan for the renewal of lighting
The UN yesterday in Cancun proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHGs) equivalent to nearly one-third of the additional reduction that needs to be realized to stabilize the Earth’s climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of compelling reduction commitments of the developed countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, the main problem in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFC released to Earth due to illumination would be avoided if the white-glowing bulbs, which so far still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better yet, by light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to 70% of the exhaust gases of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emission emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, had committed to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, from this balance sheet we would still have to deduct 5 Gt to stabilize the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020, to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white-burning bulbs 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, and with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by twice as much.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last between 6,000 and 10,000 hours on average.
The new LED bulbs, such as the ones launched by Philips this week -- which, by the way, participated in the UN study -- have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-burning bulb, implying the savings of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that these completely new bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a regular resistance.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they must therefore be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the producers provide an acceptance point.
The main source of mercury emissions on the planet, however, according to the report, is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants that emit significantly more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the white-burning pears.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report outlines in detail the profits that each country would make thanks to this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save one billion dollars a year on electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 coal-fired power plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
