The association, which explains that its findings "in view of the small number of samples analyzed do not represent a statistically significant value, but rather represent an illustration character of the treated problem," had between July and September purchased the foods usually consumed within four, from a approximately ten-year-old child to meals plus an intermediate meal at the supermarkets in Oise and Paris.
These typical meals – including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and fruit parts, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day – were examined as well as pastries from laboratories looking for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is depleting: 81 chemicals, including 42 potentially or likely carcinogenic and five potentially carcinogenic, as well as 37 endocrine-disrupting substances, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if the legal limits for each chemical substance taken individually are not exceeded in the approximate total of cases, it is very well understood from this survey that the reality in which the consumer is exposed to potentially carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrine disruptors is alarming," the association notes.
Already at breakfast alone, butter and tea with milk already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three safely proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as an intermediate meal for the study, has traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, including lunch, where the study found traces of an insecticide strictly banned in the EU.
In addition, the chopped steak, the tuna from the box, even the baguette and the chewing gum of pesticides and other chemicals were spiced.
In the tap water, the analyses have brought to light the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak with 34 determined chemical residues was the "richest", and even the plastic plate used to warm the meal in the microwave was not unloaded.
The ultimate risk of this "polluting cocktail" for the consumer "will likely be underestimated," according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV) has proposed to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides to halt the “increase in civilizational diseases” “in view of the urgency of the situation”.
In July, a European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) study identified the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
